## Section 13 — Pro Bono Litigation Incentive

### 13.1 — Purpose

The author is one individual. The entities that may infringe this license have
legal budgets that dwarf the author's personal resources. This Section establishes
an opt-in program that enables any licensed attorney to represent the author in
any dispute, proceeding, negotiation, or enforcement action arising under or
relating to this license.

### 13.2 — Attorney Opt-In

Any attorney licensed to practice law in any jurisdiction with authority over a
relevant proceeding may elect to represent the author by providing written notice
identifying: (a) the specific matter or class of matters accepted; (b) confirmation
of no disqualifying conflict with any adverse party; and (c) the attorney's
standard billing rate at the time of opt-in ("Standard Rate").

### 13.3 — Compensation

(a) **Base Rate — Regardless of Outcome.** The author compensates each
    participating attorney at their Standard Rate for all billable time spent,
    payable within thirty (30) days of invoice. This is not contingent on recovery.

(b) **Success Fee — Wins Only.** Upon any Qualifying Recovery (Section 13.4),
    the author pays a Success Fee equal to ONE PERCENT (1%) of the gross monetary
    amount of that Qualifying Recovery. The 1% pool is divided equally among all
    attorneys who actively and materially participated in obtaining that specific
    recovery. No attorney receives more than their equal proportional share.

    Example: a $5,000,000,000 Qualifying Recovery with three (3) attorneys produces
    a Success Fee pool of $50,000,000, split as $16,666,667 per attorney.

### 13.4 — Qualifying Recovery

"Qualifying Recovery" means any monetary payment actually received by the author
as a direct result of a judgment, order, settlement, consent decree, arbitration
award, or other binding resolution in which the attorney actively participated.
Qualifying Recovery includes: Supplemental Windfall Payments under Section 12,
restitution under Section 5.5, liquidated damages, punitive damages, bad-faith
litigation cost awards under Section 11(e), and attorneys' fees shifted to the
adverse party by court order. Qualifying Recovery excludes purely non-monetary
relief.

### 13.5 — No Exclusivity

The author may engage multiple attorneys simultaneously. All attorneys who
actively participated in a Qualifying Recovery share the 1% pool proportionally
by headcount for that recovery.

### 13.6 — Attorney Independence

Opt-in attorneys are independent contractors, not employees or agents of the
author. Each attorney remains bound by the rules of professional conduct of
their jurisdiction.

### 13.7 — Author Rights

The author retains the right to: (a) accept or decline any opt-in at the author's
sole discretion; (b) terminate any attorney's representation with fourteen (14)
days' written notice, subject to applicable professional conduct rules; and (c)
settle, accept, or reject any offer at the author's sole discretion without
requiring attorney consent.

### 13.8 — Standing Offer

Publication of this license constitutes a standing offer to any attorney
satisfying Section 13.2. No separate engagement agreement is required; the opt-in
notification under Section 13.2 constitutes binding acceptance of these terms.

---

## Section 14 — Defecting Counsel Fund

### 14.1 — Eligibility

Any attorney who was, at any point within the thirty-six (36) months preceding
their opt-in under Section 13.2, engaged — as in-house counsel, outside counsel,
of-counsel, or any materially equivalent capacity — by a pharmaceutical, biotech,
medical device, or health data entity that is adverse to the author in any
proceeding covered by this license, and who voluntarily terminates or withdraws
from that engagement to represent the author, qualifies as "Defecting Counsel."

### 14.2 — Enhanced Success Fee

In addition to the base-rate compensation and 1% Success Fee under Section 13.3,
each Defecting Counsel who actively and materially participates in a Qualifying
Recovery is entitled to a separate Defecting Counsel Success Fee equal to TWO
PERCENT (2%) of that Qualifying Recovery, divided equally among all Defecting
Counsel who participated in that specific recovery. This 2% pool is separate from
and cumulative with the 1% pool under Section 13.3(b).

Example: a $5,000,000,000 Qualifying Recovery with two (2) Defecting Counsel
produces a Defecting Counsel pool of $100,000,000 — split as $50,000,000 each —
in addition to each attorney's share of the $50,000,000 pool under §13.3(b).

### 14.3 — Good Faith Requirement

Defecting Counsel status applies only where the attorney switched in genuine good
faith — meaning the attorney believes the author's position has legal and factual
merit, has terminated all conflicting engagements with adverse parties consistent
with applicable professional conduct rules, and is not acting as an agent or
information conduit for any entity adverse to the author.

### 14.4 — No Double Agents — Personal Liability for Caused Losses

(a) **Prohibition.** No Defecting Counsel may simultaneously maintain, directly
    or through intermediaries, any representation, advisory, employment, or
    consulting relationship with any entity adverse to the author while
    representing the author. A single undisclosed communication with an adverse
    party that could advantage that party constitutes breach.

(b) **Personal Liability.** Any Defecting Counsel who intentionally or through
    gross negligence acts as a double agent — providing material information,
    strategy, or advantage to any entity adverse to the author while representing
    the author — is personally liable for the full amount of any losses, adverse
    judgments, settlement amounts, or damage outcomes causally attributable to the
    double-agency conduct. This liability is personal, direct, joint and several
    with any co-conspirators, and is not capped by any malpractice policy limit.

(c) **Disgorgement.** All compensation received under Sections 13 and 14 by a
    Defecting Counsel determined to have acted as a double agent is subject to
    full disgorgement — returned to the author with interest at prime rate plus
    ten percent (10%) compounded monthly from the date each payment was received.

(d) **Determination.** The author's determination of double-agency violation
    is presumptively correct. The burden of disproving causation and intent rests
    entirely on the accused attorney in any subsequent proceeding.

### 14.5 — Disclosure Obligation

Any attorney with a prior adverse-party relationship as described in Section 14.1
must disclose it in their opt-in notification. Failure to disclose is itself a
breach entitling the author to terminate representation, demand disgorgement, and
pursue all liability under Section 14.4(b). Timely full disclosure does not
disqualify an attorney from Defecting Counsel status — it is required to activate it.

### 14.6 — No Limitation on Section 13

Nothing in Section 14 reduces or modifies the rights, compensation, or eligibility
of attorneys who opt in under Section 13 with no prior adverse-party relationship.
Sections 13 and 14 operate in parallel.

